---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---
<BaseLayout
  title="Our Story &mdash; Red Fox Inn"
  description="How a 1913 bronze fox, the senator who wrote the Weeks Act, and a 1950s motor lodge on Main Street became Red Fox Inn in Lancaster, New Hampshire."
>
  <main>
    <!-- Top bar -->
    <div class="bg-night text-snow">
      <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto px-6 py-5 flex items-center justify-between">
        <a href="/" class="font-display font-light text-2xl hover:text-fox-amber transition-colors">Red Fox Inn</a>
        <a href="tel:+16037884921" class="font-body text-sm tracking-wide hover:text-fox-amber transition-colors">(603) 788&#8209;4921</a>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Hero -->
    <section class="bg-fox-brown text-snow px-6 py-36 md:py-48">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto text-center">
        <p class="font-body text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.35em] text-fox-orange mb-10 font-medium">
          Our Story
        </p>
        <h1 class="font-display font-light text-5xl md:text-7xl lg:text-[5.5rem] leading-[1.05] mb-12 text-snow">
          A New Chapter<br />on an Old Road.
        </h1>
        <p class="font-display font-light italic text-xl md:text-2xl text-fox-cream leading-relaxed max-w-3xl mx-auto">
          Red Fox Inn sits at 112 Main Street in Lancaster, New Hampshire &mdash; the county seat of Co&ouml;s County, the gateway to the Great North Woods, and a place where every view out the window exists because one local boy thought big.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 1: The Fox -->
    <section class="bg-fox-cream px-6 py-32 md:py-40">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
        <p class="font-body text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.3em] text-fox-red mb-6 font-medium">
          01 &nbsp;&middot;&nbsp; The Fox
        </p>
        <h2 class="font-display font-light text-4xl md:text-6xl leading-[1.1] mb-12">
          Lancaster&rsquo;s fox<br />is a bronze one.
        </h2>
        <div class="font-body text-lg md:text-xl text-fox-brown leading-[1.75] font-light space-y-6">
          <p>
            The red fox isn&rsquo;t just our name &mdash; it&rsquo;s Lancaster&rsquo;s official town symbol. In 1913, when Lancaster celebrated its sesquicentennial, the town commissioned sculptor <em class="font-display">Anna Vaughn Hyatt Huntington</em> to cast a fox in bronze. Huntington was no local artisan &mdash; her <em class="font-display">Joan of Arc</em> stands in Riverside Park in Manhattan, her <em class="font-display">El Cid</em> guards the entrance to the Hispanic Society of America.
          </p>
          <p>
            The bronze fox she created for Lancaster still sits in Centennial Park, three blocks from our front door.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Pull quote -->
      <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto mt-20 px-6 text-center">
        <p class="font-display font-light italic text-fox-red text-4xl md:text-5xl lg:text-6xl leading-[1.2]">
          &ldquo;Clever, caring, independent,<br />and at home with the wild.&rdquo;
        </p>
        <p class="font-body text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.3em] text-warm-gray mt-8 font-medium">
          &mdash; The Town of Lancaster, on its fox
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto mt-20">
        <p class="font-body text-lg md:text-xl text-fox-brown leading-[1.75] font-light">
          The town chose the fox for what it represents. We chose the name Red Fox Inn because no other words capture this place better.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 2: The Forest -->
    <section class="bg-snow px-6 py-32 md:py-40">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
        <p class="font-body text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.3em] text-fox-red mb-6 font-medium">
          02 &nbsp;&middot;&nbsp; The Forest
        </p>
        <h2 class="font-display font-light text-4xl md:text-6xl leading-[1.1] mb-12">
          A Lancaster kid<br />saved the mountains.
        </h2>
        <div class="font-body text-lg md:text-xl text-fox-brown leading-[1.75] font-light space-y-6">
          <p>
            Every mountain you see from Lancaster exists as protected land because of a boy who grew up on one of them. <em class="font-display">John Wingate Weeks</em> was born and raised here, went on to become a U.S. Senator and Secretary of War, and authored the Weeks Act &mdash; signed by President Taft on March 1, 1911.
          </p>
          <p>
            That single law created the White Mountain National Forest and 47 other eastern national forests, protecting over 20 million acres.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Pull quote -->
      <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto mt-20 px-6 text-center">
        <p class="font-display font-light italic text-forest-green text-4xl md:text-5xl lg:text-6xl leading-[1.2]">
          &ldquo;A Lancaster kid looked at these mountains<br />and decided they should belong to everyone.&rdquo;
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto mt-20">
        <p class="font-body text-lg md:text-xl text-fox-brown leading-[1.75] font-light">
          Weeks&rsquo;s summer lodge &mdash; a 1912 fieldstone mansion with a 56-foot observation tower &mdash; is now Weeks State Park, a five-minute drive from the inn. Stand at the top of that tower and you&rsquo;ll see the legacy of a Lancaster kid who thought big.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 3: The Town -->
    <section class="bg-fox-cream px-6 py-32 md:py-40">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
        <p class="font-body text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.3em] text-fox-red mb-6 font-medium">
          03 &nbsp;&middot;&nbsp; The Town
        </p>
        <h2 class="font-display font-light text-4xl md:text-6xl leading-[1.1] mb-12">
          Chartered in 1763.<br />Stubborn ever since.
        </h2>
        <div class="font-body text-lg md:text-xl text-fox-brown leading-[1.75] font-light space-y-6">
          <p>
            Lancaster was chartered on July 6, 1763. The first settlers arrived the following spring with twenty head of cattle and twelve acres of corn seed &mdash; only to watch a freak August frost destroy the entire crop. They stayed anyway. That stubbornness runs deep here.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Israel River that flows through downtown was called <em class="font-display">Siwooganock</em> &mdash; &ldquo;place of the burnt pine trees&rdquo; &mdash; by the Abenaki. Co&ouml;s County itself takes its name from the Abenaki word for &ldquo;white pines,&rdquo; and remains the only place name in America officially spelled with a diaeresis.
          </p>
          <p>
            Next door to the inn, St. Paul&rsquo;s Episcopal Church &mdash; built in 1876 and modeled after a small English country church &mdash; is described by the Library of Congress as one of the most photographed churches in New England. The Lancaster Fair has run every year since 1870.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Pull quote -->
      <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto mt-20 px-6 text-center">
        <p class="font-display font-light italic text-fox-red text-4xl md:text-5xl lg:text-6xl leading-[1.2]">
          &ldquo;The friendly town<br />in the friendly state.&rdquo;
        </p>
        <p class="font-body text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.3em] text-warm-gray mt-8 font-medium">
          &mdash; Lancaster&rsquo;s town motto
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 4: The Inn -->
    <section class="bg-snow px-6 py-32 md:py-40">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
        <p class="font-body text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.3em] text-fox-red mb-6 font-medium">
          04 &nbsp;&middot;&nbsp; The Inn
        </p>
        <h2 class="font-display font-light text-4xl md:text-6xl leading-[1.1] mb-12">
          A 1950s motor lodge,<br />still earning its keep.
        </h2>
        <div class="font-body text-lg md:text-xl text-fox-brown leading-[1.75] font-light space-y-6">
          <p>
            Red Fox Inn is a 27-room motor lodge at the center of downtown Lancaster. We&rsquo;re operated by <em class="font-display">Hanuram, LLC</em>, and we&rsquo;re part of a family of North Country properties that includes Eastgate Inn in Littleton and Saffron Inn in Auburn, Maine. We&rsquo;ve been in the hospitality business in this region for over eight years.
          </p>
          <p>
            The building dates to the 1950s, and we honor that heritage &mdash; the exterior-corridor format means you park at your door, whether you&rsquo;re arriving by car, motorcycle, ATV, or snowmobile. We&rsquo;ve upgraded every room with new mattresses, laminate wood floors, flat-screen TVs, fiber-optic Wi-Fi, and modern furniture, while keeping the retro character that makes a motor lodge worth staying at.
          </p>
          <p>
            We&rsquo;re not a luxury resort and we don&rsquo;t pretend to be. We&rsquo;re a warm, clean, well-run inn in one of the most beautiful small towns in America &mdash; run by people who live here and love it.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Closing pull quote -->
    <section class="bg-fox-brown text-snow px-6 py-40 md:py-56">
      <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto text-center">
        <p class="font-display font-light italic text-fox-amber text-4xl md:text-6xl lg:text-7xl leading-[1.15]">
          &ldquo;Where the North Woods<br />welcome you home.&rdquo;
        </p>
        <div class="mt-16">
          <a
            href="/stay/"
            class="font-body inline-block px-10 py-3.5 bg-fox-red text-snow font-medium tracking-wide hover:bg-deep-red transition-colors"
          >
            Plan a Visit
          </a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Footer -->
    <footer class="px-6 py-20 bg-night text-fox-cream text-sm">
      <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-12">
        <div>
          <p class="font-display font-light text-3xl text-snow mb-4">Red Fox Inn</p>
          <p class="font-body leading-relaxed font-light">
            112 Main Street<br />Lancaster, NH 03584
          </p>
          <p class="font-body mt-4">
            <a href="tel:+16037884921" class="hover:text-fox-amber transition-colors">(603) 788&#8209;4921</a>
          </p>
          <p class="font-body">
            <a href="mailto:stay@redfoxinnnh.com" class="hover:text-fox-amber transition-colors">stay@redfoxinnnh.com</a>
          </p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="font-body uppercase text-xs tracking-[0.2em] text-fox-orange mb-4 font-medium">Visit</p>
          <ul class="font-body space-y-2 font-light">
            <li><a href="/stay/" class="hover:text-snow transition-colors">Stay</a></li>
            <li><a href="/experience/" class="hover:text-snow transition-colors">Experience</a></li>
            <li><a href="/journal/" class="hover:text-snow transition-colors">Journal</a></li>
            <li><a href="/story/" class="hover:text-snow transition-colors">Story</a></li>
            <li><a href="/policies/" class="hover:text-snow transition-colors">Policies</a></li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="font-body uppercase text-xs tracking-[0.2em] text-fox-orange mb-4 font-medium">The fine print</p>
          <p class="font-body leading-relaxed font-light">
            A 27-room independent inn in Co&ouml;s County, New Hampshire. Between the White Mountain National Forest and the Connecticut River.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </footer>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
